=========================================
🔥 TOP 50 STL INTERVIEW QUESTIONS (C++ STl)
=========================================

========================
1. STL BASICS (1–10)
========================

1. What is STL?
A: Standard Template Library (containers + algorithms + iterators).

2. What are STL components?
A: Containers, Algorithms, Iterators.

3. Why STL is used?
A: Reusability, efficiency, faster development.

4. What are containers?
A: Objects that store data (vector, map, set).

5. Types of containers?
A: Sequence, Associative, Unordered, Adapters.

6. What are algorithms in STL?
A: Predefined functions (sort, find, count).

7. What are iterators?
A: Pointer-like objects to access containers.

8. What is begin()?
A: Points to first element.

9. What is end()?
A: Points past last element.

10. What is STL advantage?
A: Generic, fast, reusable code.

-----------------------------------------

========================
2. VECTOR (11–18)
========================

11. What is vector?
A: Dynamic array.

12. Is vector contiguous?
A: Yes.

13. Time complexity of push_back?
A: O(1) amortized.

14. Why vector reallocation happens?
A: Capacity full.

15. What is vector growth?
A: Usually doubles size.

16. Difference size vs capacity?
A: size = elements, capacity = allocated memory.

17. What is vector reallocation?
A: New memory + copy old elements.

18. Is vector good for front insertion?
A: No (O(n)).

-----------------------------------------

========================
3. DEQUE (19–23)
========================

19. What is deque?
A: Double-ended queue.

20. Is deque contiguous?
A: No.

21. Complexity of push_front?
A: O(1)

22. Difference vector vs deque?
A: vector = contiguous, deque = block memory.

23. Why deque used in STL?
A: Fast front and back operations.

-----------------------------------------

========================
4. LIST (24–28)
========================

24. What is list?
A: Doubly linked list.

25. Is list contiguous?
A: No.

26. Why list used?
A: Fast insert/erase anywhere.

27. Random access in list?
A: Not supported.

28. Why list slower in practice?
A: Poor cache locality.

-----------------------------------------

========================
5. STACK / QUEUE (29–35)
========================

29. What is stack?
A: LIFO container adaptor.

30. What is queue?
A: FIFO container adaptor.

31. Default container for stack?
A: deque.

32. Default container for queue?
A: deque.

33. Can stack use vector?
A: Yes.

34. Can queue use vector?
A: No (needs pop_front).

35. Do stack/queue support iterators?
A: No.

-----------------------------------------

========================
6. PRIORITY QUEUE (36–40)
========================

36. What is priority queue?
A: Heap-based container.

37. Default behavior?
A: Max heap.

38. How to make min heap?
A: priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>>.

39. Underlying structure?
A: Heap (vector-based).

40. Time complexity of push/pop?
A: O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

========================
7. SET / MAP (41–46)
========================

41. What is set?
A: Sorted unique elements.

42. What is multiset?
A: Sorted elements with duplicates.

43. What is map?
A: Key-value sorted structure.

44. What is multimap?
A: Map with duplicate keys.

45. Internal structure of map?
A: Red-Black Tree.

46. Complexity of map operations?
A: O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

========================
8. UNORDERED MAP / SET (47–50)
========================

47. What is unordered_map?
A: Hash table key-value store.

48. What is unordered_set?
A: Hash set.

49. Average complexity unordered_map?
A: O(1)

50. Difference map vs unordered_map?
A: map = sorted (tree), unordered_map = hash table.

